kind of just continued to pass on all the job openings to their friends they linked in again

484
00:26:06,291 --> 00:26:12,396
sorry and places like Facebook and everywhere else that you know they can kind of just spread the

485
00:26:12,436 --> 00:26:13,757
word and you know you

486
00:26:15,079 --> 00:26:18,448
I've never asked them to, it's just something that if you're excited about where you work,

487
00:26:18,568 --> 00:26:22,158
that's kind of, you know, you want your friends and other people to work with you.

488
00:26:24,907 --> 00:26:30,830
Yeah, I mean, I've already said some of these. There's some great, I know not all this generation,

489
00:26:30,890 --> 00:26:37,293
you guys that are here now are on Facebook, but there's some great diversity game Facebook pages

490
00:26:37,333 --> 00:26:43,156
that I really rely on. Of course, Discord groups for sure. Twitter, we were working with an eSports

491
00:26:43,216 --> 00:26:48,979
company and I had to really source a lot on Twitter, because that's where they were. We

492
00:26:48,999 --> 00:26:53,622
try to go to where they are and dig deep in that space.

493
00:26:55,144 --> 00:26:58,427
And I know it sounds like we've touched on that a couple times too, is that a lot of

494
00:26:58,447 --> 00:27:02,251
the places that we're reaching out to or we're looking for people, it's like they're already

495
00:27:02,311 --> 00:27:04,553
in games, they're already working games.

496
00:27:05,013 --> 00:27:11,800
So is there anything that you can suggest to people that aren't in the industry yet?

497
00:27:12,801 --> 00:27:14,683
What if they're just starting out in their search?

498
00:27:16,420 --> 00:27:20,665
I would say go to events, go to game jams, career fairs, find a mentor.

499
00:27:21,425 --> 00:27:22,747
You know, this helps you in a few ways.

500
00:27:23,107 --> 00:27:28,412
It helps you network, it gets you new portfolio pieces, it helps you practice interviewing

501
00:27:28,452 --> 00:27:30,915
skills and it helps you build relationships.

502
00:27:34,780 --> 00:27:37,102
Relationships are key, right?

503
00:27:37,282 --> 00:27:38,763
For everything you'll ever do, right?

504
00:27:39,283 --> 00:27:42,365
So I always say show up to any game events.

505
00:27:42,445 --> 00:27:44,727
If you don't have any in the town you're in,

506
00:27:45,127 --> 00:27:46,127
start a game meetup.

507
00:27:46,167 --> 00:27:49,510
There's a lot of people who probably would appreciate that.

508
00:27:51,398 --> 00:27:56,019
If you're an introvert, that's really your superpower because you can really focus on

509
00:27:56,059 --> 00:27:56,679
what you're doing.

510
00:27:57,100 --> 00:28:03,841
But when you go to any of these meetups or game jams, I always say, you know, come prepared

511
00:28:03,902 --> 00:28:08,463
with maybe in your head three questions that you can be ready to ask at any time.

512
00:28:08,603 --> 00:28:11,984
Because if you're in a situation where you don't know who's sitting next to you, you

513
00:28:12,024 --> 00:28:14,325
can come up with like, oh, what game are you working on?

514
00:28:15,045 --> 00:28:20,846
or, you know, what, are you using Unity or Unreal, you know, just get the conversation started.

515
00:28:21,326 --> 00:28:25,887
And a lot of times that's a relief for everybody in the room or anybody you're next to talking.

516
00:28:26,988 --> 00:28:31,309
I also like to go to, you know, to events and kind of force myself and go,

517
00:28:31,409 --> 00:28:34,110
okay, here are my three questions I'm going to ask.

518
00:28:34,670 --> 00:28:36,751
you know, just to have in my back pocket.

519
00:28:37,072 --> 00:28:38,393
But also I'm gonna give myself,

520
00:28:38,793 --> 00:28:41,696
I'm gonna meet six people before I leave this thing tonight.

521
00:28:41,996 --> 00:28:44,138
So I kind of, I'm competitive with myself

522
00:28:44,678 --> 00:28:48,261
and try to come up with the six people I've met at that.

523
00:28:49,084 --> 00:28:52,789
that event. That's awesome advice, even at any level, I think.

524
00:28:53,169 --> 00:28:57,334
Yeah, definitely. So next I want to touch on the interview process.

525
00:28:57,935 --> 00:29:01,219
So what's it like when, you know, there's a match, there's a job you get,

526
00:29:01,239 --> 00:29:02,921
the recruiter wants to have a call.

527
00:29:05,404 --> 00:29:09,068
What is it like when you're ready to start the interview process?

528
00:29:09,208 --> 00:29:11,110
So how does it start off?

529
00:29:11,170 --> 00:29:13,712
Absolutely. Internally, it really is recruiting first.

530
00:29:13,952 --> 00:29:16,094
We do the whole verbal checkbox, the actual human being.

531
00:29:16,775 --> 00:29:18,737
And then from there, the hiring manager.

532
00:29:19,017 --> 00:29:22,300
And then if that goes well, then we go into a panel interview,

533
00:29:22,320 --> 00:29:25,924
which will be a full interview, mostly five hours, depending on the studio.

534
00:29:26,284 --> 00:29:28,106
And then from there, it'll be a hire and no hire decision.

535
00:29:29,402 --> 00:29:32,003
Yeah, and Alejandro mentioned the five hour interview.

536
00:29:32,203 --> 00:29:34,724
That's after four other interviews, usually,

537
00:29:34,744 --> 00:29:35,624
in this industry.

538
00:29:35,764 --> 00:29:39,165
So we like to try to be as thorough as possible

539
00:29:39,206 --> 00:29:42,207
in our pre-screen, our initial conversation with candidates,

540
00:29:42,247 --> 00:29:45,448
so that we can at least skip one step when submitting

541
00:29:45,488 --> 00:29:48,569
to our client and get the process moving a little more

542
00:29:48,629 --> 00:29:48,969
quickly.

543
00:29:50,023 --> 00:29:55,865
And if the client wants to set up the interview, which happens every day, we like to prep our

544
00:29:55,905 --> 00:29:57,046
candidates beforehand.

545
00:29:57,106 --> 00:29:58,907
We go through a list of questions.

546
00:29:59,387 --> 00:30:07,010
Even the most seasoned developers or whatever, it just really helps ease the interview process.

547
00:30:07,450 --> 00:30:10,711
I don't care how smart you are, in the interview process your brain freezes.

548
00:30:11,092 --> 00:30:12,052
That's just human.

549
00:30:12,472 --> 00:30:15,453
So it's always good to practice and we try to do that.

550
00:30:15,533 --> 00:30:16,654
And then afterwards we...

551
00:30:17,815 --> 00:30:21,079
have a debrief so we can keep, you know, kind of hear what they're thinking,

552
00:30:21,099 --> 00:30:26,607
if they have new ideas or, you know, questions about that company they just interviewed.

553
00:30:28,350 --> 00:30:32,556
Yeah, we just kind of make sure we're aligning the whole process every step of the way.

554
00:30:35,213 --> 00:30:37,155
I think that brings up a good point.

555
00:30:37,195 --> 00:30:39,978
What can the candidate do to prepare for the interview?

556
00:30:39,998 --> 00:30:42,200
So it sounds like some people do some preps.

557
00:30:42,460 --> 00:30:46,184
I'm curious what else could be suggested to a candidate

558
00:30:46,204 --> 00:30:48,406
to make sure that the interview goes smoothly.

559
00:30:48,446 --> 00:30:49,587
And are there any sort of things

560
00:30:49,627 --> 00:30:51,209
that hiring managers are looking for?

561
00:30:51,606 --> 00:30:55,288
Absolutely. I mean, before anything, Kami, that's really well said.

562
00:30:55,469 --> 00:30:59,331
Honestly, as you as an interviewer, it's like much like public speaking. So

563
00:31:01,693 --> 00:31:06,696
practice and hone in your interview key talking points. You should be able to succinctly answer

564
00:31:06,736 --> 00:31:11,259
your questions through your experience. Practice explaining the challenges you've had, right?

565
00:31:12,059 --> 00:31:17,263
And how your company or how you as a person have grown into something better after that.

566
00:31:21,125 --> 00:31:24,227
You know, find out as much as you can about the role.

567
00:31:24,788 --> 00:31:28,611
I've had a couple people who have just shown up

568
00:31:28,631 --> 00:31:31,813
to the interview and not even really known

569
00:31:31,853 --> 00:31:34,716
what they were there for, and that's an instant downer.

570
00:31:34,876 --> 00:31:38,118
So, you know, just absolutely do your research.

571
00:31:39,721 --> 00:31:45,266
Yep, and I'll say just some of the things I thought were obvious, but maybe not.

572
00:31:45,886 --> 00:31:52,031
Everything's been on video for the last couple of years, so look professional, don't vape,

573
00:31:52,432 --> 00:31:53,132
don't eat.

574
00:31:54,033 --> 00:32:00,439
Believe me, these things have happened, so yeah, just make sure you show up like you

575
00:32:00,479 --> 00:32:02,200
would to an in-person interview.

576
00:32:03,430 --> 00:32:08,315
So there's a couple other things, besides the obvious things, do your research on the

577
00:32:08,355 --> 00:32:14,801
company itself, understand the culture, understand the project or the company's product, know

578
00:32:14,821 --> 00:32:20,286
the games, play the games, do your research on the interviewers that you're going to be

579
00:32:20,326 --> 00:32:24,970
talking to, go to LinkedIn, again, LinkedIn, sorry, we're definitely plugging them today.

580
00:32:26,912 --> 00:32:28,093
Have excitement for the role.

581
00:32:29,222 --> 00:32:34,648
Be there, be jazzed, pay full attention, turn off discord, turn off your phone,

582
00:32:35,229 --> 00:32:38,112
you know, slack, everything. Definitely be yourself.

583
00:32:39,104 --> 00:32:44,267
You know, just you're going to be working with these people for 40 hours a week.

584
00:32:44,347 --> 00:32:46,748
So, you know, you want you want to be your genuine self.

585
00:32:47,668 --> 00:32:49,229
And there's also additional things.

586
00:32:50,190 --> 00:32:51,791
Speak to your experiences in general.

587
00:32:52,491 --> 00:32:55,012
Wrap your answers up in a past story if you can.

588
00:32:55,132 --> 00:32:58,154
This helps see the context of something you've done personally

589
00:32:58,194 --> 00:33:00,255
and allows us to dig deeper if we want details.

590
00:33:01,215 --> 00:33:02,637
And play up your successes.

591
00:33:03,097 --> 00:33:04,739
This is really important.

592
00:33:05,720 --> 00:33:08,662
You have done awesome things, and you should be proud of that.

593
00:33:08,782 --> 00:33:11,325
So just brag about it.

594
00:33:12,305 --> 00:33:14,447
What this does is help me look for character traits

595
00:33:14,487 --> 00:33:15,268
and competencies.

596
00:33:15,348 --> 00:33:18,311
So just for an example, did you build a custom engine

597
00:33:18,331 --> 00:33:18,951
just because?

598
00:33:19,452 --> 00:33:22,415
This shows me that you've got a growth mindset,

599
00:33:22,455 --> 00:33:24,576
that you're driven, that you're curious.

600
00:33:26,158 --> 00:33:28,441
Do you work with artists, engineers, and producers?

601
00:33:28,541 --> 00:33:31,766
This shows me that you can cross communicate

602
00:33:31,806 --> 00:33:34,229
and you can work in groups.

603
00:33:34,390 --> 00:33:36,853
It's not just can you do the job that we're hiring for,

604
00:33:36,933 --> 00:33:38,656
but how can you compliment and add

605
00:33:38,696 --> 00:33:41,159
to the studio's team and value?

606
00:33:41,720 --> 00:33:41,880
Oops.

607
00:33:42,461 --> 00:33:44,441
Yeah, adding value, that one's huge.

608
00:33:44,501 --> 00:33:47,582
So I always suggest that people write things down the night before,

609
00:33:47,602 --> 00:33:51,323
because bringing things back from their long term memory can be really hard.

610
00:33:51,483 --> 00:33:55,844
So if you prepare for it, then you'll have all of those top of mind

611
00:33:55,884 --> 00:33:56,844
when you go into the interview.

612
00:33:57,184 --> 00:34:00,485
And also, one other thing I want to add is ask questions, be curious.

613
00:34:01,045 --> 00:34:03,425
So at the end, you never want to go, do you have any questions for me?

614
00:34:03,485 --> 00:34:04,305
And then you're like, no.

615
00:34:05,446 --> 00:34:06,046
And then that's it.

616
00:34:08,005 --> 00:34:09,645
prepare some questions before as well.

617
00:34:09,725 --> 00:34:10,886
So that's super important.

618
00:34:11,066 --> 00:34:13,907
I can't stress how much you need to ask questions.

619
00:34:14,407 --> 00:34:14,687
Yes.

620
00:34:16,007 --> 00:34:18,889
And so I want to bring up testing.

621
00:34:20,369 --> 00:34:23,150
Tests can be a reality in the industry.

622
00:34:23,630 --> 00:34:26,351
Some studios do them, some studios don't.

623
00:34:27,311 --> 00:34:29,472
So this is actually geared more towards hiring managers.

624
00:34:29,512 --> 00:34:32,013
So what advice do you have for hiring managers

625
00:34:32,053 --> 00:34:32,753
that come to you and say,

626
00:34:32,793 --> 00:34:34,774
hey, I wanna give a test for this role?

627
00:34:35,847 --> 00:34:40,311
I would actually ask that you think about if you really need to test at all, because

628
00:34:40,351 --> 00:34:44,914
many companies are ditching them and a lot of candidates won't take them anymore.

629
00:34:45,975 --> 00:34:50,498
And you know, if you really feel that you do need to give them, you need to let recruiters

630
00:34:50,538 --> 00:34:53,580
and candidates know that you're going to give a test right away because it's, you know,

631
00:34:54,161 --> 00:34:58,164
it's just a waste of your time if you get through a phone screen and they just won't

632
00:34:58,204 --> 00:35:02,146
test it and they won't take it and you've just wasted both parties' times.

633
00:35:03,584 --> 00:35:06,305
And so what if a test is part of the process?

634
00:35:06,345 --> 00:35:08,346
How should a candidate prepare if they have to take one?

635
00:35:09,166 --> 00:35:14,429
Well, I think that, you know, the best way to do that is to understand the product that they make

636
00:35:15,430 --> 00:35:18,952
and understand, again, the position that you're going for very well.

637
00:35:19,012 --> 00:35:23,574
Do the research on the position because you may be able to, you know, combine the two

638
00:35:23,814 --> 00:35:26,015
and it would help you give you an advantage possibly.

639
00:35:27,254 --> 00:35:28,254
I'd like to follow up with that.

640
00:35:28,555 --> 00:35:29,755
Ask questions, again.

641
00:35:30,415 --> 00:35:31,636
If you're taking a test and you don't know,

642
00:35:31,916 --> 00:35:34,177
lawyers don't know, ask questions.

643
00:35:34,257 --> 00:35:36,337
If they can't answer it, then they can't answer it for you.

644
00:35:36,677 --> 00:35:39,158
And if they can, then you've got an answer to the question.

645
00:35:39,358 --> 00:35:41,899
So be curious.

646
00:35:42,459 --> 00:35:43,480
Can I just jump in there?

647
00:35:43,580 --> 00:35:46,321
You should never be afraid to ask a hiring manager

648
00:35:46,341 --> 00:35:47,861
and or a recruiter a question,

649
00:35:47,881 --> 00:35:50,662
because that's just really good.

650
00:35:50,742 --> 00:35:52,463
Don't be, yeah, just don't be afraid.

651
00:35:52,803 --> 00:35:55,224
It shows that you're interested in the job.

652
00:35:55,835 --> 00:35:59,538
Absolutely. Really well said.

653
00:35:59,698 --> 00:36:03,501
All right, so candidates interviewed, they've taken the test, the team is deliberating on next

654
00:36:03,541 --> 00:36:07,704
steps. Maybe they're talking to a couple other candidates as well about the same role. So how

655
00:36:07,744 --> 00:36:12,788
do you all make sure that a candidate has a good experience as they interview? What are some things

656
00:36:12,808 --> 00:36:18,312
that you all do personally for candidate experience? A lot of communication, give a 48

657
00:36:18,793 --> 00:36:22,195
hour turnaround time on a decision if they're the only candidate.

658
00:36:23,062 --> 00:36:25,703
If they're not the only candidate, it comes down to transparency.

659
00:36:25,743 --> 00:36:26,284
Let them know.

660
00:36:26,304 --> 00:36:29,986
You don't want to basically dangle a carrot and, you know, let's just not

661
00:36:30,366 --> 00:36:31,107
communicate with them.

662
00:36:31,627 --> 00:36:37,030
It's really disrespectful for you to, you know, just for people's time, for

663
00:36:37,070 --> 00:36:37,751
them not to have it.

664
00:36:39,265 --> 00:36:41,806
And as Nellie already mentioned, communication is key.

665
00:36:41,906 --> 00:36:43,406
Just keeping candidates in the loop.

666
00:36:43,586 --> 00:36:44,726
We will not ghost you.

667
00:36:44,786 --> 00:36:47,027
We'll make sure that we're following up regularly.

668
00:36:47,487 --> 00:36:49,007
If we haven't heard from a studio,

669
00:36:49,427 --> 00:36:50,888
we'll let you know we haven't heard

670
00:36:50,948 --> 00:36:53,028
and that we'll have feedback as soon as we do here.

671
00:36:53,348 --> 00:36:54,448
We will share it with you.

672
00:36:56,029 --> 00:36:58,609
And if we end up hearing from the client

673
00:36:58,649 --> 00:37:00,609
after you've interviewed and the interview didn't go

674
00:37:00,910 --> 00:37:03,070
as well as you'd hoped, we will still let you know.

675
00:37:03,090 --> 00:37:06,071
And we'll keep moving forward,

676
00:37:06,151 --> 00:37:07,711
keep pushing for the next opportunity.

677
00:37:09,265 --> 00:37:13,390
So that brings me to the awkward piece that none of us like,

678
00:37:13,470 --> 00:37:15,732
is what do we have to do when we have to reject the candidate?

679
00:37:15,892 --> 00:37:21,298
Either skill set didn't align or just, I guess,

680
00:37:21,998 --> 00:37:23,159
how do you reject a candidate?

681
00:37:23,179 --> 00:37:25,362
Is there anything that can be done to make sure

682
00:37:25,382 --> 00:37:28,305
that that's a constructive learning experience

683
00:37:28,365 --> 00:37:30,086
as opposed to a generic email?

684
00:37:32,024 --> 00:37:36,670
You know, I always collect feedback after an interview from the people that have interviewed

685
00:37:36,690 --> 00:37:43,360
them and I curate it and I send it to the recruiter and it depends if the person wants

686
00:37:43,380 --> 00:37:44,201
feedback or not.

687
00:37:44,382 --> 00:37:46,745
If they do, I'm always willing to give it to them.

688
00:37:47,926 --> 00:37:49,606
I as a recruiter really appreciate what you just said.

689
00:37:51,227 --> 00:37:53,267
It is really important for people to be able to interview

690
00:37:53,307 --> 00:37:54,448
and grow from their experiences.

691
00:37:55,588 --> 00:37:57,708
Normally, most companies can never really send you

692
00:37:57,768 --> 00:37:58,849
a spoiler-free email saying,

693
00:37:58,889 --> 00:38:00,269
hey, it didn't work out this time,

694
00:38:00,309 --> 00:38:01,129
I want another candidate.

695
00:38:01,569 --> 00:38:04,830
But I ask you, every time you receive one of those emails,

696
00:38:04,870 --> 00:38:07,011
go back and ask, hey, is there any feedback we can have?

697
00:38:07,511 --> 00:38:10,592
And normally, we're asking to go on the phone with them.

698
00:38:10,892 --> 00:38:13,312
Normally, we can talk to you about the experience,

699
00:38:13,452 --> 00:38:15,353
and over the phone we can share with you what we can.

700
00:38:17,465 --> 00:38:18,506
All right, so the flip side of that.

701
00:38:18,966 --> 00:38:20,809
Interviews go really well, you're gonna get an offer.

702
00:38:20,989 --> 00:38:24,433
So, woo!

703
00:38:24,473 --> 00:38:26,435
But before we dig into that,

704
00:38:26,475 --> 00:38:27,897
I think it's important to talk a little bit more

705
00:38:27,917 --> 00:38:31,321
about what the market's like right now.

706
00:38:31,341 --> 00:38:33,083
So, Cammie, can you tell us a little bit

707
00:38:33,103 --> 00:38:33,864
about what you're seeing?

708
00:38:34,264 --> 00:38:35,405
Yeah, the market is hot.

709
00:38:35,525 --> 00:38:36,386
It's really active.

710
00:38:37,329 --> 00:38:38,550
It's almost exhausting.

711
00:38:40,731 --> 00:38:43,974
Studios have a lot of hires across the board.

712
00:38:43,994 --> 00:38:45,415
We're seeing that all over.

713
00:38:47,096 --> 00:38:49,338
But when we work with studios, when

714
00:38:49,378 --> 00:38:51,500
we sign up working with the studio,

715
00:38:51,540 --> 00:38:57,124
we really emphasize that they're ready to make the offer quickly.

716
00:38:58,045 --> 00:39:00,547
If they interview someone and they wait for weeks

717
00:39:00,587 --> 00:39:02,469
to come back with an offer, they're

718
00:39:02,489 --> 00:39:03,529
going to lose the candidate.

719
00:39:05,111 --> 00:39:06,912
Candidates don't have to wait anymore.

